 font-size:12pt">TIINs are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">more user-friendly document</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> than the Impact Assessments </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(IA) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">they replaced.  However</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">I have some concerns about t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he methodology behind them.  The methodology for preparing IAs is publicly available, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">common across Whitehall, and includes expert ext</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ernal scrutiny.  It </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">also has</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> European and intern</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ational comparators.  In contras</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t the TIIN instructions are internal </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">HMRC </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">documents, subject to change wi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">thout notice, and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">there is no </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">external consultation or quality control.  I suggest the TIIN instructions should be published, and that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">any </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">changes to them should </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">first </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">be subject to external consultation.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Impact assessments </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">are archived at </span><a href="http://www.legislation.gov.uk/search/impacts"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.legislation.gov.uk/search/impacts</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and are searchable by department and topic. TIINs however are inconsistently filed and those that are online are not searchable: see </span><a href="http://www.hmrc.gov.uk/thelibrary/tiins.htm"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.hmrc.gov.uk/thelibrary/tiins.htm</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  I suggest that HMRC and HMT should appoin</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t and fund an archivist tasked to:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.78pt; padding-left:4.22pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">index and make searchable the TIINs produced to date so that they are at </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">minimum as accessible and retrievable as IAs and</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="2" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.33pt; padding-left:3.67pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">establish a methodology for archiving of future TIINs in either the IA library or an equivalent TIIN library</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e main issue I see with TIINs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> however,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> is why are they undertaken at all?</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  I would suggest that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> TIIN, like an IA, should be both a tool to help decide between policy options (by setting out the costs, benefits and imp</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">acts of the different options that might be used to achieve a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> policy objective</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">at the consultation stage of policy development, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> also</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> as</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> a way of expl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">aining the merits of a final</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> policy decision.  But published TIINs don't seem to do that.  See, for example, the TIIN for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the reform of legislation applicable to Controlled Foreign Companies (at </span><a href="http://www.hmrc.gov.uk/budget2012/tiin-0724.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.hmrc.gov.uk/budget2012/tiin-0724.pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> ) which is clear that the costs of the reform will amount to £175 million this year, rising to £805 million by 2016/17</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, but where the benefits to be achieved by incurring these costs </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">are an </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">unquantified</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and unspecific increase in "competitiveness".  I would suggest that a TIIN could usefully contain an unequivocal statement of:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.78pt; padding-left:4.22pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Expected costs and benefits</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="2" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.33pt; padding-left:3.67pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Expected impacts (such as on equality) and</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="3" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.1pt; padding-left:4.9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Expected date of review of whether the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> expected costs and benefits have arisen </span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It would seem to me that it would improve tax policy making if these commitments were codified in the TIIN methodology and the methodology made public.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">January 2014</span></p></div></body></html>